# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: serilog-dotnet-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A **data model** is an abstract model that organizes elements of data and standardizes how they relate to one another and to the properties of real-world entities.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] For instance, a data model may specify that the data element representing a car be composed of a number of other elements which, in turn, represent the color and size of the car and define its owner.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The corresponding professional activity is called generally *data modeling* or, more specifically, *database design*.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data models are typically specified by a data expert, data specialist, data scientist, data librarian, or a data scholar.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data modeling language and notation are often represented in graphical form as diagrams.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model can sometimes be referred to as a data structure, especially in the context of programming languages.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data models are often complemented by function models, especially in the context of enterprise models.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the *structure of data*; conversely, **structured data** is data organized according to an explicit data model or data structure.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Structured data is in contrast to *unstructured data* and *semi-structured data*.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The term ***data model*** can refer to two distinct but closely related concepts.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Sometimes it refers to an abstract formalization of the objects and relationships found in a particular application domain: for example the customers, products, and orders found in a manufacturing organization.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] At other times it refers to the set of concepts used in defining such formalizations: for example concepts such as entities, attributes, relations, or tables.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] So the "data model" of a banking application may be defined using the entity–relationship "data model".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This article uses the term in both senses.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Managing large quantities of structured and unstructured data is a primary function of information systems.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data models describe the structure, manipulation, and integrity aspects of the data stored in data management systems such as relational databases.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] They may also describe data with a looser structure, such as word processing documents, email messages, pictures, digital audio, and video: XDM, for example, provides a data model for XML documents.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The main aim of data models is to support the development of information systems by providing the definition and format of data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] According to West and Fowler (1999) "if this is done consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The results of this are indicated above.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] However, systems and interfaces often cost more than they should, to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A major cause is that the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The reason for these problems is a lack of standards that will ensure that data models will both meet business needs and be consistent.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the structure of data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Typical applications of data models include database models, design of information systems, and enabling exchange of data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Logical data model: describes the semantics, as represented by a particular data manipulation technology.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This consists of descriptions of tables and columns, object oriented classes, and XML tags, among other things.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Physical data model: describes the physical means by which data are stored.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This is concerned with partitions, CPUs, tablespaces, and the like.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The significance of this approach, according to ANSI, is that it allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent with the other model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The table/column structure may be different from a direct translation of the entity classes and attributes, but it must ultimately carry out the objectives of the conceptual entity class structure.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Early phases of many software development projects emphasize the design of a conceptual data model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Such a design can be detailed into a logical data model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In later stages, this model may be translated into physical data model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] However, it is also possible to implement a conceptual model directly.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] One of the earliest pioneering works in modeling information systems was done by Young and Kent (1958), who argued for "a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] They wanted to create "a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Their work was the first effort to create an abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine-independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In the 1960s data modeling gained more significance with the initiation of the management information system (MIS) concept.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] According to Leondes (2002), "during that time, the information system provided the data and information for management purposes.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The first generation database system, called Integrated Data Store (IDS), was designed by Charles Bachman at General Electric.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Two famous database models, the network data model and the hierarchical data model, were proposed during this period of time".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Codd worked out his theories of data arrangement, and proposed the relational model for database management based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In the 1970s entity–relationship modeling emerged as a new type of conceptual data modeling, originally formalized in 1976 by Peter Chen.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Entity–relationship models were being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This technique can describe any ontology, i.e., an overview and classification of concepts and their relationships, for a certain area of interest.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Nijssen developed "Natural Language Information Analysis Method" (NIAM) method, and developed this in the 1980s in cooperation with Terry Halpin into Object–Role Modeling (ORM).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] However, it was Terry Halpin's 1989 PhD thesis that created the formal foundation on which Object–Role Modeling is based.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Bill Kent, in his 1978 book *Data and Reality,* compared a data model to a map of a territory, emphasizing that in the real world, "highways are not painted red, rivers don't have county lines running down the middle, and you can't see contour lines on a mountain".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In contrast to other researchers who tried to create models that were mathematically clean and elegant, Kent emphasized the essential messiness of the real world, and the task of the data modeler to create order out of chaos without excessively distorting the truth.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Harrington (2000), "the development of the object-oriented paradigm brought about a fundamental change in the way we look at data and the procedures that operate on data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Traditionally, data and procedures have been stored separately: the data and their relationship in a database, the procedures in an application program.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] During the early 1990s, three Dutch mathematicians Guido Bakema, Harm van der Lek, and JanPieter Zwart, continued the development on the work of G.M.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] They focused more on the communication part of the semantics.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In 1997 they formalized the method Fully Communication Oriented Information Modeling FCO-IM.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A database model is a specification describing how a database is structured and used.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Several such models have been suggested.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This may not strictly qualify as a data model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The flat (or table) model consists of a single, two-dimensional array of data elements, where all members of a given column are assumed to be similar values, and all members of a row are assumed to be related to one another.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The hierarchical model is similar to the network model except that links in the hierarchical model form a tree structure, while the network model allows arbitrary graph.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] , organizes data using two fundamental constructs, called records and sets.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Records (or nodes) contain fields (i.e. attributes), and sets (or edges) define one-to-many, many-to-many and many-to-one relationships between records: one owner, many members.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The network data model is an abstraction of the design concept used in the implementation of databases.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Network models emphasise interconnectedness, making them ideal for applications where relationships are crucial, like social networks or recommendation systems.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This structure allows for efficient querying of relationships without expensive joins.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] is a database model based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Its core idea is to describe a database as a collection of predicates over a finite set of predicate variables, describing constraints on the possible values and combinations of values.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The power of the relational data model lies in its mathematical foundations and a simple user-level paradigm.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A method of data modeling that has been defined as "attribute free", and "fact-based".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The result is a verifiably correct system, from which other common artifacts, such as ERD, UML, and semantic models may be derived.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Associations between data objects are described during the database design procedure, such that normalization is an inevitable result of the process.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The simplest style of data warehouse schema.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The star schema consists of a few "fact tables" (possibly only one, justifying the name) referencing any number of "dimension tables".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data structure diagram (DSD) is a diagram and data model used to describe conceptual data models by providing graphical notations which document entities and their relationships, and the constraints that bind them.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The basic graphic elements of DSDs are boxes, representing entities, and arrows, representing relationships.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are most useful for documenting complex data entities.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are an extension of the entity–relationship model (ER model).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In DSDs, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as boxes composed of attributes which specify the constraints that bind entities together.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] DSDs differ from the ER model in that the ER model focuses on the relationships between different entities, whereas DSDs focus on the relationships of the elements within an entity and enable users to fully see the links and relationships between each entity.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with the notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The choices are between arrow heads, inverted arrow heads (crow's feet), or numerical representation of the cardinality.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] An entity–relationship model (ERM), sometimes referred to as an entity–relationship diagram (ERD), could be used to represent an abstract conceptual data model (or semantic data model or physical data model) used in software engineering to represent structured data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] There are several notations used for ERMs.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Like DSD's, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as lines, with the relationship constraints as descriptions on the line.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The E-R model, while robust, can become visually cumbersome when representing entities with several attributes.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with a notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model in Geographic information systems is a mathematical construct for representing geographic objects or surfaces as data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Generic data models are developed as an approach to solving some shortcomings of conventional data models.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] For example, different modelers usually produce different conventional data models of the same domain.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This can lead to difficulty in bringing the models of different people together and is an obstacle for data exchange and data integration.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Invariably, however, this difference is attributable to different levels of abstraction in the models and differences in the kinds of facts that can be instantiated (the semantic expression capabilities of the models).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The modelers need to communicate and agree on certain elements that are to be rendered more concretely, in order to make the differences less significant.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A semantic data model in software engineering is a technique to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A semantic data model is an abstraction that defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A semantic data model is sometimes called a conceptual data model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The logical data structure of a database management system (DBMS), whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., are symbolically defined within physical data stores.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data architecture is the design of data for use in defining the target state and the subsequent planning needed to hit the target state.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data architecture describes the data structures used by a business and/or its applications.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] There are descriptions of data in storage and data in motion; descriptions of data stores, data groups, and data items; and mappings of those data artifacts to data qualities, applications, locations, etc.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Essential to realizing the target state, Data architecture describes how data is processed, stored, and utilized in a given system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It provides criteria for data processing operations that make it possible to design data flows and also control the flow of data in the system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data modeling in software engineering is the process of creating a data model by applying formal data model descriptions using data modeling techniques.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data modeling is a technique for defining business requirements for a database.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It is sometimes called *database modeling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The figure illustrates the way data models are developed and used today.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A conceptual data model is developed based on the data requirements for the application that is being developed, perhaps in the context of an activity model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The data model will normally consist of entity types, attributes, relationships, integrity rules, and the definitions of those objects.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This is then used as the start point for interface or database design.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Another kind of data model describes how to organize data using a database management system or other data management technology.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It describes, for example, relational tables and columns or object-oriented classes and attributes.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Such a data model is sometimes referred to as the *physical data model*, but in the original ANSI three schema architecture, it is called "logical".
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In that architecture, the physical model describes the storage media (cylinders, tracks, and tablespaces).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Ideally, this model is derived from the more conceptual data model described above.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It may differ, however, to account for constraints like processing capacity and usage patterns.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A different approach is to use adaptive systems such as artificial neural networks that can autonomously create implicit models of data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data structure is a way of storing data in a computer so that it can be used efficiently.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It is an organization of mathematical and logical concepts of data.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Often a carefully chosen data structure will allow the most efficient algorithm to be used.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The choice of the data structure often begins from the choice of an abstract data type.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model describes the structure of the data within a given domain and, by implication, the underlying structure of that domain itself.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This means that a data model in fact specifies a dedicated *grammar* for a dedicated artificial language for that domain.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model represents classes of entities (kinds of things) about which a company wishes to hold information, the attributes of that information, and relationships among those entities and (often implicit) relationships among those attributes.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The model describes the organization of the data to some extent irrespective of how data might be represented in a computer system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The entities represented by a data model can be the tangible entities, but models that include such concrete entity classes tend to change over time.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Robust data models often identify abstractions of such entities.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] For example, a data model might include an entity class called "Person", representing all the people who interact with an organization.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Such an abstract entity class is typically more appropriate than ones called "Vendor" or "Employee", which identify specific roles played by those people.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model *instance*, i.e. applying a data model *theory* to create a practical data model *instance* for some particular application.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] For example, in the relational model, the structural part is based on a modified concept of the mathematical relation; the integrity part is expressed in first-order logic and the manipulation part is expressed using the relational algebra, tuple calculus and domain calculus.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data model instance is created by applying a data model theory.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This is typically done to solve some business enterprise requirement.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Business requirements are normally captured by a semantic logical data model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This is transformed into a physical data model instance from which is generated a physical database.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] For example, a data modeler may use a data modeling tool to create an entity–relationship model of the corporate data repository of some business enterprise.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] This model is transformed into a relational model, which in turn generates a relational database.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Patterns are common data modeling structures that occur in many data models.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data-flow diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the "flow" of data through an information system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It differs from the flowchart as it shows the *data* flow instead of the *control* flow of the program.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] A data-flow diagram can also be used for the visualization of data processing (structured design).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Data-flow diagrams were invented by Larry Constantine, the original developer of structured design, based on Martin and Estrin's "data-flow graph" model of computation.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It is common practice to draw a context-level data-flow diagram first which shows the interaction between the system and outside entities.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The **DFD** is designed to show how a system is divided into smaller portions and to highlight the flow of data between those parts.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] An Information model is not a type of data model, but more or less an alternative model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Within the field of software engineering, both a data model and an information model can be abstract, formal representations of entity types that include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] According to Lee (1999) an information model is a representation of concepts, relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements for the domain context.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] More in general the term *information model* is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In those cases the concept is specialised to Facility Information Model, Building Information Model, Plant Information Model, etc.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity–relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] An object model in computer science is a collection of objects or classes through which a program can examine and manipulate some specific parts of its world.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In other words, the object-oriented interface to some service or system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Such an interface is said to be the *object model of* the represented service or system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] For example, the Document Object Model (DOM) [1] is a collection of objects that represent a page in a web browser, used by script programs to examine and dynamically change the page.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] There is a Microsoft Excel object model for controlling Microsoft Excel from another program, and the ASCOM Telescope Driver is an object model for controlling an astronomical telescope.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] In computing the term *object model* has a distinct second meaning of the general properties of objects in a specific computer programming language, technology, notation or methodology that uses them.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] For example, the *Java object model*, the *COM object model*, or *the object model of OMT*.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Such object models are usually defined using concepts such as class, message, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] There is an extensive literature on formalized object models as a subset of the formal semantics of programming languages.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling (ORM) is a method for conceptual modeling, and can be used as a tool for information and rules analysis.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling is a fact-oriented method for performing systems analysis at the conceptual level.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The quality of a database application depends critically on its design.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] To help ensure correctness, clarity, adaptability and productivity, information systems are best specified first at the conceptual level, using concepts and language that people can readily understand.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The conceptual design may include data, process and behavioral perspectives, and the actual DBMS used to implement the design might be based on one of many logical data models (relational, hierarchic, network, object-oriented, etc.).
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized general-purpose modeling language in the field of software engineering.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] It is a graphical language for visualizing, specifying, constructing, and documenting the artifacts of a software-intensive system.
[src:serilog-dotnet-lib/structured-data] UML offers a mix of functional models, data models, and database models.
